item.title: The Temporary Nature of Persuasion
item.dc:creator: armin
item.content:encoded:
Introduction

Communication between political elites and their constituencies is believed to be an important driver of public opinion. This form of communication is one-directional and typically takes the form of statements made by leaders that are intended to persuade the electorate to support a specific policy or political figure, i.e., to move popular opinion closer to a desired position. Despite some early scholars doubts about the persuasive effects of mass communication (), more contemporary research provides overwhelming evidence for its importance in shaping public perception of political issues (e.g.: ; ; ; ).

However, the effects of mass communication appear to be short-lived, decaying after a period of just a few weeks, or even several days (; ). This issue is of immediate practical relevance to political communication, and from an academic perspective, questions concerning the durability of communication effects have significant implications for the study of public opinion. Depending on their longevity, such effects might either be an effective long-term means of controlling public opinion or a cause of short-term disturbances.

The present lack of clarity around this issue is caused, at least in part, by methodological challenges. The fields reliance on survey-experimental methods means that there have historically been limited opportunities to manipulate temporal variables. In most cases, survey-based experiments present a stimulus and immediately collect respondents reactions. While it is possible to survey responses repeatedly, it remains debatable whether an experimental stimulus can have the same impact over time as real-world communication it is possible that because the stimuli are known to be artificial, they will not be accorded the same weight and so may not be remembered with equal clarity.

More precisely, the greatest challenge faced by survey-based experimental designs in seeking to control for the effects of time is that they lack the impact of an actual highly salient real-life event. Researchers carefully design their stimuli to resemble the real world, employing artificial versions of persuasive arguments, campaign ads, facial displays, and the like. Still, the situation a survey respondent finds themselves in is highly unnatural, and it remains debatable whether these experimental stimuli succeed in reproducing the effects of exposure to real-world communication ().

This paper addresses those challenges by applying a different method utilizing a natural experiment that allows for better manipulation of the dimension of time. Specifically, this paper examines public reactions to the EU-Turkey statement given on 18 March 2016, which was widely recognized as marking the formal closure of the Balkan route. Although this statement announced a policy change intended to reduce flows of refugees traveling to Central, Northern and Western Europe it took six months to produce the promised effect. As a result, this scenario allowed for the experimental separation of the statement itself from the outcome of the policy that was announced.

The EU-Turkey statement was a high-profile announcement about an issue that was very salient to everyone living in Germany at the time, making the event an excellent opportunity to study the effects of persuasive political communication. The announcement was also made during the 22nd wave of the German Internet Panel (GIP). The GIP offers dense, high-quality data for March 2016, allowing the time variation of the announcements effect to be examined on a day-to-day basis by applying a difference-in-difference methodological approach.

The results below show that communication does have a casual effects on respondents perceptions, policy preferences and voting intentions. Respondents were more likely to view refugee inflows as manageable, less supportive of security policies oriented toward refugees, and less likely to vote for the far-right Alternative for Germany party (AfD). However, the effects were strongest for respondents surveyed one and two days after the statement was given, and then declined over time.

These findings suggest that communication effects are short-lived. Even politically salient information such as the Balkan routes closure, which is clearly linked to a desirable change in circumstances, does not permanently affect attitudes towards the political issue on which it bears most directly (i.e., migration). These findings also demonstrate the relative advantages of studies using natural, real-world communication over more traditional survey-based methods when it comes to assessing the time-dimension of communication effects.

Communication and the Time Dimension

In recent years possibilities in political communication to address large audiences have become increasingly available. Blumler () prominently argues that we have reached a more complex era of communication where the value of public service broadcasting has diminished and an increasing number of media voices, and political elites can communicate more directly with their audiences.

In this environment, political actors find various ways to mobilize and persuade their audiences. There is an increasing focus on social media platform such as Facebook and Twitter (; ), but also personalized political advertising, speeches and press releases have been shown to affect public opinion (). Persuasion research has a long history in communication research going back to the "Message Learning Theory" (; ). This early conception understands persuasion as recipients willingness to receive persuasive communications, and its key ideas still hold in the more complex modern media landscape. The core qualities of the actors who intend to persuade audiences according to "Message Learning Theory" are that they are perceived as intending to inform rather than convince. Thus, messages are most effective if they include strong points and credible information.

The increasing complexity of the media landscape suggests that citizen might be increasingly overwhelmed by the amount of information they receive. Consequently, a critical reflection of persuasive communication effects durability is in vital for a better understanding of political communication in times of mass communication. The basic concepts of the "Message Learning Theory" and Arnolds () idea of how communication influences policy preferences help to explain the role of time in a case such as the EU-Turkey statement. Arnold argues that communication must be causally linked to citizens preferred policy outcomes to affect peoples preferences. From his viewpoint, causally linked communication, communication that credibly conveys a desirable outcome, changes an individuals perception of circumstance (see also for a more recent empiric study).

In the contribution at hand, I argue that this causal link and the resulting change in perception are crucial to the longevity of communication effects. In the case of communication on a policy change such as the closure of the Balkan route, the causal link between the announcement and the proposed outcome would be the strongest immediately following the announcement. The more time passes after the announcement, the weaker the causal link becomes, as the novelty of the proposed outcomes wears off. I assume this dynamic since citizens are believed to have stable key values and real demands (; ). Consequently, communication that introduces new information can only cause a brief disruption of opinion but, in the long term, a real change that satisfies citizens demands will be necessary. The agnostic treatment of time in previous analyses of mass communication is most likely a result of methodological constrains. Most contributions approach questions on communication effects using survey experiments, a design which only allows limited control over the time dimension in relation to the treatment. This time-invariant perspective on the effect of information asses the immediate reaction to a piece of information without clear evidence if the presented information will have a lasting effect on attitudes towards an issue or policy the information relates to. Additionally, the artificial scenarios, candidates, and information used in experimental designs have a tendency to overestimate the effect of information communicated (; ; ).

Just as media systems have changed, so too have the tools available to research them. An alternative approach to traditional experimental designs is to explore the presentation of information in a natural experiment post-factually. A natural experiment allows to exploit a truly salient issue and observe the impact of a related piece of information across time. Thus, the established idea that survey experimental designs allow establishing causality while regular observational studies do not is no longer valid. Designs such as Regression Discontinuity, Difference-in-Difference or systemic control allow establishing causality post factually with existing data sources.

The Case of the European Refugee Crisis

The scenario that I exploit for this purpose is the 2015/16 European Refugee Crisis. In 2015 an unprecedented wave of asylum seekers and refugees found their way to Europe, representing the greatest refugee crisis since the Second World War. Over 1.2 million first-time asylum applications were lodged in the EU Member States in 2015, Germany being one of the preferred destinations. Such large-scale human movement was primarily the result of a series of revolutions and civil wars in North Africa and the Middle East, commonly referred to as the "Arab Spring." The crisis peaked in Germany during the second half of 2015. The German public administration was unable to cope with the rising influx of asylum seekers, most of whom could only apply several months after they arrived in Germany ().

On March 18 2016, EU Heads of State and Turkey agreed to end irregular migration from Turkey to the EU. The so-called EU-Turkey Statement vouched to replace disorganized, chaotic, irregular and dangerous migratory flows by organized, safe and legal pathways to Europe for those entitled to international protection in line with EU and international law (). Despite many critical voices the EU-Turkey Agreement was mostly framed as the official closure of the Balkan route (e.g.: ; ; ; ).

The European refugee crisis scenario and the resulting EU-Turkey statement is ideal for the post-factual study of the time function of political information on public opinion. We can expect a time-based treatment variable that measures the exposure to the Balkan road closure announcement to be highly efficient as it was at the time, citizens have been heavily invested in the issue and were very likely to be exposed to the announcement immediately after it was given. In line with Arnold () the proposal of a formal closure of the Balkan route provides a strong causal link to a positive outcome, in this case reducing refugee influx. Finally, the scenario allows testing the impact of communication that is most likely to affect attitudes towards asylum policy in an environment where the migration issue is of high salience and citizen base their attitudes on key values.

Hypotheses

I now make predictions about how the information about the closure of the Balkan route will affect opinions. As previously argued I expect communication to affect attitudes through the perception of the issue. Accordingly, respondents exposed to the EU-Turkey statement will be more likely to perceive the refugee inflow as manageable.

Further, I expect this effect to extend to policy preference and voting behaviour. If respondents perception of the severity of refugee inflows changes it can also be expected that that their demand for security policy will decline. I expect respondents to be less likely to demand security policy after the the statement was given. At the same time parties had a varying focus on migration policy during the refugee crisis. Due to change in perception of the situation I expect respondents to be less likely to support the AfD which strongly supported anti-migration policy.

Previous contributions have paid little attention to a time dimension when analyzing the effect of information. When I regard the effect of information across time I assume citizen to have stable () preferences based on real demands (), especially in the context of the European refugee crisis (). Unless these real demands are met information can only disturb preference but fails to have a lasting effect as in the case of the Balkan route closure the expected outcome was only archived several month after it was announced. Consequently, I expect all of the described effects to be strongest immediately after the announcement was given and to decline over time for respondents surveyed further after the statement was given.

Empirical Strategy

In this contribution I apply the Unexpected Event during Surveys Design (UESD) formalized by Muoz et al. () to capture the effect of the EU-Turkey statement on public sentiments. Similar to Regression Discontinuity Designs UESD enables the identification of causal effects by exploiting the occurrence of an unexpected event during the fieldwork of a survey in order to estimate its causal effect on the relevant outcome by comparing the responses of the individuals interviewed prior to the event.

Due to the late release of the EUs press release on 18 March (), I assume that people that were surveyed on 19th or later were exposed to the announcement and those before were not. More precisely, the exposure to the announcement can be described as follows:

$$X_{i} = \begin{cases} \text{1 if } d_i \geq {19 } \\ \text{0 if } d_i< {19} \end{cases};$$

where Xi describes the news exposure and equates to one if respondents were questioned on the 19th or after. i describes respondents in the GIP sample and di the day of survey completion.

Identifying a causal effect based on a sample of respondents questioned before and after an event relies on multiple assumptions. The design applied in this paper involves two main assumptions, as described by Muoz et al. (). The first is Excludability: every discrepancy between respondents questioned before and after the incident is the sole product of the event. That is, the interview time will only impact the dependent variable by an event that took place at the defined cutoff point. Therefore, certain factors may happen that render the pre- and post-event conditions different and thus affect the answer given by the respondents, violating the assumption of Excludability.

The second main principle is Ignorability: for every respondent, the possible consequences must be independent of the interview moment. Therefore, in order for time to be a valid instrument of the event, assignment to separate time values should be autonomous from the dependent variable. It ensures the assignment of the interview time will be as good as random.

In order to examine the deterioration of communication effects over time, I test my treatment variable across different sub-samples. These sub-samples are selected on the basis of the date the respondent completed the survey. Thus, the first sub-sample only includes respondents survey one day before or after the cutoff and the last sub-sample all respondents surveyed up to twelve days before or after the cutoff. This way the control and treatment groups are always equally sized.

For each of these sub-samples I will run, depending on the outcome variables scaling, a simple cross-sectional logistic or multinomial regression. The models will be specified as follows:

Yi=0+1Xi+i;

where Yi specifies the outcome variable and Xi the treatment variable. In the robustness section of this paper I will also present regression results of models including a set of demographic controls.

Inspired by , this contribution presents simulated predicted values to provide the most reader-friendly measures possible as well as to account for fundamental uncertainty in my data. More precisely, I will calculate and present the differences in predicted values between the treatment and control groups.

I use these models and predicted values to evaluate the treatments effect on respondents perception of the crisis, their policy preferences and voting intentions. I will discuss the operationalization of these more in detail in the subsequent section.

Data

The requirement to apply the UESD and also to be able to test the longevity of the effect is survey data that provides a dense sample of respondents around the cutoff. The German Internet Panel (GIP) provides survey data for March 2016 which allows an analysis of the announcements effect on public opinion across time. The sample was collected throughout March and contains 3141 observations while respondents could enter the survey any day of the month according to an elaborate sampling strategy which will be disused more in detail in the next section.

This 22nd wave of the GIP includes a question asking respondents to chose between pro-refugee policy and security policy with the question:

In your opinion, how should politicians deal with this possible dilemma? Either one can fulfill the moral obligation to help refugees from war zones to help. Or you can guarantee security in German society. 1

The GIP also surveys opinions about Germanys ability to cope with refugees inflows using the following statement on a likert scale of agreement:

Germany can cope with the challenges posed by the influx of refugees.2

Additionally, the vote intention for all major parties is surveyed ().

I create a dummy from the ability to cope question to evaluate whether the treatment variable affects the respondents perception of the refugee influx. The dummy evaluates to one if a respondent agrees or strongly agrees to the statement and zero otherwise to measure my dependent variables. For evaluating policy preferences, I create a three-level nominal variable that specifies if respondents favour a focus on refugee support, security policy or both policies equally. For vote intentions, I create a set of dummies for each party which evaluate to one if the respondent intents to vote for the respective party and zero otherwise.

Threats to Identification

Subsequently I discuss various threats to the presented identification strategy, starting with threats to Excludability. The first potential source of bias are fluctuations in refugee inflows. They could be expected to change as the reduction of refugee inflow is the proposed aim of the announced agreement with Turkey. As figure [descrip] (a) demonstrates, the number of refugees in March is only slightly lower than those in February and on a similar level compared to April. A significant decrease in asylum applications can only be found from October 2016 after a slight increase in August and September. While monthly data does not exclude the possibility of variations throughout March, these findings strongly suggest that the presented measure is not biased by fluctuations in refugee inflows.

A further potential issue is other events which happened in the period before the announcement such as the Bautzen3 and Claunitz Attacks4 or the riots during new years celebrations in Cologne5. Figure [descrip] (b) provides a rough estimate of issue salience based on Google trend data (see for testings of Google trend data as a salience measure ; ). The figure shows that while other issues were highly salient in mid to end of February, the Total Interest Over Time6 fell to a low level in March. Thus, I conclude that these effects are highly unlikely to still affect the perception of the ability to cope or the vote intention for the AfD in the period used for this analysis.

Yet another challenge to Excludability is the endogenous timing of the speech. The German government and the EU were under severe pressure to announce convincing measures to handle the inflow of refugees. Mostly because a potential deal had the intention to satisfy public opinion and discourage support for far-right parties. However, if we understand the negotiations between the EU and Turkey as a bargaining process (), either side could not solely control the conclusion of the negations. Accordingly, the timing of the occurrence of the event is not endogenous to the described dependent variables. Additionally, I will present placebo test in the robustness section of this paper to further support the fulfilment of the Excludability assumption.

The next major threat to identification is Ignorability. Ignorability is usually challenged due to insufficiently rigorous sampling strategies. The GIP is mostly conducted as a surveys online but while online surveys are often associated with insufficient sampling and self-selection bias the GIP uses a three-stage probability sample to counteract these issues. Primary sampling units (PSUs) are sampled. PSU drawing is stratified by state, government district, and urban level. For each PSU interviewers list households along a random route with a random starting point. Each household along the predefined route was listed to prevent errors and interviewer cheating and enable detailed checking of the addresses listed. Different interviewers conducted the listing and interview at all sample points. The listing yielded the third stage sampling frame. A fixed set of addresses per PSU was drawn at random start intervals to minimize clustering, (). Considering this elaborate methodology, I assume sampling to be as good as random and the Ignorability assumption to be fulfilled.

Descriptive Statistics


Before the analysis, I descriptively examine the treatment and control groups in terms of their differences. Table [groupcomp] in the appendix shows the p-values resulting from a two-sided t-test evaluating the significant difference of means between treatment and control group across different demographic features and different bandwidth used in the analysis. Equally, it presents the size of the bandwidth sub-samples and the treatment and control groups respective size. I test several demographic characteristics that could shape the respondent evaluation of the ability to cope and their vote intention. Included are dummies for respondents who live in East Germany, have an Abitur (Germany higher education entrance qualification), have a university degree, are unemployed, are over 65 years old and the respondents gender. The table shows that treatment and control only differ marginally. Of the described features, only in the 11 and 12-day bandwidth people who are 65 or older as well as respondents with or without Abitur in the first wave differ significantly between treatment and control. Accordingly, respondents surveyed before and after the announcement are highly comparable in terms of their demographic features.

Now that I have established the treatment and control groups comparability, I will examine the dependent variables around the cutoff point. Figure 6 shows the change in the means for the output variables in March 2016.

The data shows that the proportion of respondents who view the influx of refugees as manageable increased after the EU-Turkey Statement. On the 18th 31% of respondents thought that the refugee influx was manageable, 47% did so after the announcement on the 19th. A negative trend follows this increase, and the lowest proportion observed on the 24th, where the only 17% of respondents saw the refugee flows as manageable.

There is an increase in respondents who consider refugee support and security policy to be equally important in terms of policy preferences, right after the EU-Turkey statement was announced. On the 18th, only 42% of respondents thought that both policies were equally important, while on the 19th, 64% did so. At the same time, we see a sharp decline in the proportion of respondents who thought security policy was more important. On the 18th, 36% of respondents considered security policy to be the most important, while only 13% held that opinion one day later.

For vote intentions, it can be observed that the share of voting intentions for all parties but the AfD increases between four and six percentage points after the statement has been made. The FDP shows the lowest increase of four percentage points and the Greens the highest increase of eight percentage points. The decline in the expected vote share for the AfD is most decisive as they archive their second-highest indented vote share of the month one day before the announcement was made, with 13% and their lowest share of one percentage point one day after the announcement. However, this decline is only temporary and voting shares for the AfD rose again immediately afterwards, until they achieve their highest share of 15% nine days after the EU-Turkey statement.

Overall, the descriptive examination of the dependent variables points in the direction that the announcement only has a short-term effect on attitudes that fades after a few days.

Results

Subsequently I discuss various regression results testing the effect of the treatment on the assessment of the ability to cope, policy preferences and respondents voting intentions. The regression tables of the models used throughout the section can be found in appendix 12.

Figure [fd_plots] shows simulated differences between treatment and control across the different bandwidths for the respondents assessment of the ability to cope. The results are derived from a set of logistic regressions across the different bandwidths, i.e the different sub-samples that vary daily from one day before and after the treatment upto twelve days before and after the treatment. The figure shows that only in the narrow bandwidths respondents in the treatment and control group have significantly different attitudes on Germanys ability to cope. Also, there is no significant difference in simulated predicted values for the narrowest bandwidths, one day around the cutoff. This finding is likely due to the small size of the sub-sample. Finally, the results in the bandwidth two and three days around the cutoff show that people are on average 12% and 10% more likely to think that Germany can handle the inflow of refugees.

The formal Balkan route closure announcement affected the perception of refugee influx to Germany, thus confirming my key hypothesis. The results also support the idea of communication effects short-lived nature. In the case at hand, respondents are only affected in an immediate response to communication.

Figure 7 shows the simulated predicted differences from a set of multinomial models regressing the respondents policy preference on the treatment variable. The results show that the Balkan route closures announcement affects policy preferences. Respondents surveyed immediately after the information became public are on average 20% more likely to think support for refugees and security are equally important and 20% less likely to respond that security should be a priority. For wider bandwidths, the difference in simulated predicted probability approaches zero until it is no longer significant. Eventually, the treatment and control groups probability to think that both policies are equally important is no longer significantly different from the four-day bandwidth on. We can find the same for the difference in probability to prefer security policy after eight days.

The announcement of the Balkan routes closure does not affect the likelihood that respondents would prefer refugee policy. In combination with the negative effect on preferences for security policy, the results suggest that the Balkan route closures announcement mitigated the fears related to a higher level of migration rather than mobilising support for refugees.

Again both previously formulated expectations are met. The announcement of the EU-Turkey statement did affect policy preferences but only temporary. Consequently, these results provide further evidence for the importance of time when trying to understand the effect of communication on public opinion.

Figure 8 shows differences in simulated predicted values between the treatment and control group for the respondents voting intention. The differences are based on a set of logit regressions capturing the effect of the EU-Turkey statement on the intention to vote for the six major German parties. The results show that besides the intention to vote for the AfD and the FDP, citizens intentions to vote for any of the other parties are unaffected by the announcement. The results for the AfD demonstrate the same time trend as the previous results. The wider the bandwidth, the closer the difference between the two groups deviates towards zero. Thus, in the one-day bandwidth respondents are on average, 8% less likely to vote for the AfD. In contrast, respondents within the seven-day bandwidth are on average, 4% less likely to intend to vote for the AfD. Between the eight and eleven-day bandwidth treatment and control group showed no significant difference while in the twelve-day bandwidth, people are on average 3% less likely to vote for the AfD.

These results further demonstrate the decline of communication effects over time while the insignificant results in bandwidths eight and eleven might be due to the respective sample size.

For the FDP, there are only significant negative differences in bandwidths nine to twelve. In conjunction with the corresponding regression coefficients, there is a slight declining trend of the negative effect. The Green Party also shows a significant positive difference in bandwidth of twelve. The fact that we do not find these effects for smaller bandwidths is likely due to the smaller sample sizes and relatively lower intended voting shares observed for these parties. We can attest that the announcement negatively affected vote intentions for the FDP and positively affected the intention to vote for the Greens. However, the results do not allow any interpretation of the longevity of these effects.

Robustness Checks

I use a Generalized Information Matrix Test (GIM) as described by King and Roberts (), to test whether the models used for analysis are miss-specified. The GIM will test miss-specification based on discrepancies between robust and classical error calculations utilizing parametric bootstrap for the variance matrix of the test statistic. The authors specify a rule-of-thumb value with a threshold value of 1.5. If the rule-of-thumb value is below the threshold the model is correctly specified, otherwise there is a specification problem. The rule-of-thumb values for all the estimated models applied in the subsequent analysis are below the threshold, and therefore the presented models are correctly specified. (see table for the GIM rule-of-thumb values [matrix_test]). The results demonstrate that the use of robust errors is not advised.

I have previously shown in table [groupcomp] that treatment and control groups only differ marginally across the different bandwidths. To further demonstrate the robustness of the presented results, I test whether the results also hold for a set of socioeconomic controls. For this purpose I replicated the models presented previously including a set dummies for various socio-economic characteristics. These include: respondents from East-Germany formerly, holding a university entrance qualification (Abitur), holding a university degree, and for unemployed respondents, over 65 years old or female.

Section 12.1 in the appendix presents the resulting regression tables. Throughout the different presented models the coefficients only differ slightly which can be expected after adding additional covariates. The coefficients still shows the the significant results as previously presented as well as the decline across wider bandwidths. Yet, the covariates seem to slightly improve the model fit and we now find a significant positive effect of our treatment for the Green party in the two-day and twelve-day bandwidth. The observed coefficients suggest that also for Green party vote intentions the effect of the treatment variable declines over time.

As previously stated, the ability to cope variable initially has an ordinal scale that was turned into a dummy identifying the respondents who think Germany can handle the refugee influx challenges. To eliminate the possibility that this change in variable scaling introduced any bias, I ran an ordinal logit model using the variables original scaling (see table [regtab_ologit]). I also plotted simulated predicted values for each level which can be seen in figure 9. The results again confirm the previously presented findings. Up to a bandwidth size of four days around cutoff respondents are less likely to respond with a disagreement or strong disagreement to the ability to cope question and more likely to respond with the agreement or complete agreement while the likelihood for respondents to neither agree nor disagree is not significantly different between treatment and control.

I discussed the threats to the different aspects of the identification of the causal effect within the UESD model. Complimentary, I present a set of placebo test to further support the assumption that the included time-based dummy variable measures the exposure to the EU-Turkey announcement and no unobserved time trend. I ran placebo tests for all outcome variables. Additionally, I test the effect of the treatment on attitudes towards an environmental toll in German city centers as an external variable which I would not expect to be affected by the treatment. All test results can be found in section 13 in the appendix.

The test entailed a replication of the previously used models without controls while moving the cut off point daily from the 14th to the 24th of March. For each model, I used a three-day bandwidth. In those cases where we found significant results we always did so at least up to the three-day bandwidth which is why it was chosen for this test.

The results show that as soon as the threshold is moved even one day, the time dummy is no longer having a significant effect. With one exception, this can be found for all of the outcome variables. The exception is that if the treatment cut-off for the policy preference variable is set at March 22, the corresponding model shows that the respondents are more likely to support security policy after that day.

When reviewing the possible reasons for this finding, one possible explanation is the planned suicide bombings in Belgium on 22 March 2016. While more testing would be needed to establish a causal relationship between the event and the effect identified, the recognition of this finding and the Brussels attacks strongly suggest that this is not a random occurrence. However, there is a clear downward bias as of 22 March, which puts into perspective our finding that the negative treatment effect is no longer significant after 22 March. However, we do find that the treatment effect is declining before that date. In the context of the results for the other outcome variables, the evidence for declining mass communication effects remains intact.

Finally, I run a set of logit regressions using the same design applied for the analysis of the ability to cope and vote intentions. The chosen alternative placebo outcome variable asks respondents whether they support or reject environmental tolls for cars in German city centers. The results show no effect of the treatment variable, as was expected.

Overall, the placebo tests presented are further evidence that the presented time dummy indeed measures the exposure to the EU-Turkey announcement and is not susceptible to any omitted time trend.

Conclusion

Applying a natural experiment to the announcement of the Balkan route closure allowed this article to examine the longevity of mass communication effects. While previous contributions have attested various effects of communication on public opinion, from changes in vote choice to changes in policy preferences (e.g.: ; ; ), little was previously known about how those effects persist over time. That lack of knowledge was due, in part, to inherent limitations of survey-based experimental designs.

The present article overcame those limitations by relying on survey sampling of reactions to a real-world political announcement, measuring changes in public opinion in response to the EU-Turkey statement announcing the Balkan route closure. The results show that the announcement significantly affected public opinion around the issue as well as policy preferences and voting intentions. All three effects were strongest immediately after the announcement was given, and faded quickly over the course of the subsequent week. This study thus concurs with previous findings () that the persuasive effects of mass communication are temporary.

These results put previous findings about the efficacy of media effects into perspective by demonstrating the limited longevity of their effects. They also reinforce previous suggestions that scholars should avoid presenting composite or average mass communication findings that fail to discuss the degree of deterioration of the effect they presents ().

Building on these insights into the temporal dimension of mass communication, a clear avenue for future research would be to further explore the role of time in mass communication. For instance, one necessary step is to replicate the results presented here in a variety of contexts, as natural experimental designs have limited external validity. Further, it would be a valuable insight to the see how different forms of mass communication such as political advertising, televised speeches, or policy announcements fair differently across time.

Another take-way from this contribution is the value of applying research techniques that are outside the methodological norm. While survey-experimental designs have taught us much about how mass communication affects public opinion, modern survey data allow us to post-factually examine reactions to real-world events. Designs derived from Regression Discontinuity, as demonstrated in the current study, along with difference-in-difference designs or even synthetic controls, can offer revealing new perspectives on the uses and effects of communication.

Understanding the temporal dimension of mass communication is also crucial for policymakers. If the effects of mass communication do in fact deteriorate over time, as the present results strongly suggest, policymakers may need to adopt methods such as presenting a consistent stream of message-aligned communication if they wish to sustain beneficial effects. However, even that method may have limits. In the present example, government and media communication about the Balkan route closure was frequent and consistent, and only one key event the EU-Turkey statement that initially provided the new information about the Balkan route closure significantly affected public opinion. These results strongly suggest that to affect citizens opinions, policymakers will have to time their communication carefully.

I received my PhD from the University of Glasgow and hold a dual Master's degree in Political Communication and Political Science from the Universities of Amsterdam and Mannheim. Throughout my doctoral studies I also visited the European University Institute in Florence and the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.

My research focuses on how political actors and institutions shape political attitudes, as well as the implications of these shifts for democratic governance and the European Union.

In the EUDENTIFY project, lead by Theresa Kuhn, we aim to develop an integrated theory of the EU institutions-identity-link, considering variations across different policy areas and timeframes. My specific role in the project involves estimating a new European Identity as well as a European Media Mood Measure using a newly constructed dataset that spans 50 years of survey data and 20 years of EU media coverage, respectively.
